are strings.","pos":[15224,15377],"source":"If your app performs extensive culture-specific sorts of string data, you can work with the <xref:System.Globalization.SortKey> class to compare strings."},{"content":"A sort key reflects the culture-specific sort weights, including the alphabetic, case, and diacritic weights of a particular string.","pos":[15378,15510]},{"content":"Because comparisons using sort keys are binary, they are faster than comparisons that use a <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Globalization.CompareInfo&gt;</ph> object either implicitly or explicitly.","pos":[15511,15682],"source":" Because comparisons using sort keys are binary, they are faster than comparisons that use a <xref:System.Globalization.CompareInfo> object either implicitly or explicitly."},{"content":"You create a culture-specific sort key for a particular string by passing the string to the <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Globalization.CompareInfo.GetSortKey%2A?displayProperty=nameWithType&gt;</ph> method.","pos":[15683,15865],"source":" You create a culture-specific sort key for a particular string by passing the string to the <xref:System.Globalization.CompareInfo.GetSortKey%2A?displayProperty=nameWithType> method."},{"content":"The following example is similar to the previous example.","pos":[15867,15924]},{"content":"However, instead of calling the <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Array.Sort%28System.Array%29?displayProperty=nameWithType&gt;</ph> method, which implicitly calls the <ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;xref:System.Globalization.CompareInfo.Compare%2A?displayProperty=nameWithType&gt;</ph> method, it defines an <ph id=\"ph3\">&lt;xref:System.Collections.Generic.IComparer%601?displayProperty=nameWithType&gt;</ph> implementation that compares sort keys, which it instantiates and passes to the <ph id=\"ph4\">&lt;xref:System.Array.Sort%60%601%28%60%600%5B%5D%2CSystem.Collections.Generic.IComparer%7B%60%600%7D%29?displayProperty=nameWithType&gt;</ph> method.","pos":[15925,16462],"source":" However, instead of calling the <xref:System.Array.Sort%28System.Array%29?displayProperty=nameWithType> method, which implicitly calls the <xref:System.Globalization.CompareInfo.Compare%2A?displayProperty=nameWithType> method, it defines an <xref:System.Collections.Generic.IComparer%601?displayProperty=nameWithType> implementation that compares sort keys, which it instantiates and passes to the <xref:System.Array.Sort%60%601%28%60%600%5B%5D%2CSystem.Collections.Generic.IComparer%7B%60%600%7D%29?displayProperty=nameWithType> method."},{"pos":[16744,16770],"content":"Avoid string concatenation","linkify":"Avoid string concatenation","nodes":[{"content":"Avoid string concatenation","pos":[0,26]}]},{"content":"If at all possible, avoid using composite strings that are built at run time from concatenated phrases.","pos":[16772,16875]},{"content":"Composite strings are difficult to localize, because they often assume a grammatical order in the app's original language that does not apply to other localized languages.","pos":[16876,17047]},{"pos":[17052,17074],"content":"Handle dates and times","linkify":"Handle dates and times","nodes":[{"content":"Handle dates and times","pos":[0,22]}]},{"content":"How you handle date and time values depends on whether they are displayed in the user interface or persisted.","pos":[17076,17185]},{"content":"This section examines both usages.","pos":[17186,17220]},{"content":"It also discusses how you can handle time zone differences and arithmetic operations when working with dates and times.","pos":[17221,17340]},{"pos":[17346,17369],"content":"Display dates and times","linkify":"Display dates and times","nodes":[{"content":"Display dates and times","pos":[0,23]}]},{"content":"Typically, when dates and times are displayed in the user interface, you should use the formatting conventions of the user's culture, which is defined by the <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Globalization.CultureInfo.CurrentCulture%2A?displayProperty=nameWithType&gt;</ph> property and by the <ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;xref:System.Globalization.DateTimeFormatInfo&gt;</ph> object returned by the <ph id=\"ph3\">`CultureInfo.CurrentCulture.DateTimeFormat`</ph> property.","pos":[17371,17759],"source":"Typically, when dates and times are displayed in the user interface, you should use the formatting conventions of the user's culture, which is defined by the <xref:System.Globalization.CultureInfo.CurrentCulture%2A?displayProperty=nameWithType> property and by the <xref:System.Globalization.DateTimeFormatInfo> object returned by the `CultureInfo.CurrentCulture.DateTimeFormat` property."},{"content":"The formatting conventions of the current culture are automatically used when you format a date by using any of these methods:","pos":[17760,17886]},{"pos":[17890,17975],"content":"The parameterless <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.DateTime.ToString?displayProperty=nameWithType&gt;</ph> method","source":"The parameterless <xref:System.DateTime.ToString?displayProperty=nameWithType> method"},{"pos":[17979,18101],"content":"The <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.DateTime.ToString%28System.String%29?displayProperty=nameWithType&gt;</ph> method, which includes a format string","source":"The <xref:System.DateTime.ToString%28System.String%29?displayProperty=nameWithType> method, which includes a format string"},{"pos":[18105,18196],"content":"The parameterless <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.DateTimeOffset.ToString?displayProperty=nameWithType&gt;</ph> method","source":"The parameterless <xref:System.DateTimeOffset.ToString?displayProperty=nameWithType> method"},{"pos":[18200,18321],"content":"The <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.DateTimeOffset.ToString%28System.String%29?displayProperty=nameWithType&gt;</ph>, which includes a format string","source":"The <xref:System.DateTimeOffset.ToString%28System.String%29?displayProperty=nameWithType>, which includes a format string"},{"pos":[18325,18446],"content":"The <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>composite formatting<ept id=\"p1\">](../../../docs/standard/base-types/composite-formatting.md)</ept> feature, when it is used with dates","source":"The [composite formatting](../../../docs/standard/base-types/composite-formatting.md) feature, when it is used with dates"},{"content":"The following example displays sunrise and sunset data twice for October 11, 2012.","pos":[18448,18530]},{"content":"It first sets the current culture to Croatian (Croatia), and then to English (Great Britain).","pos":[18531,18624]},{"content":"In each case, the dates and times are displayed in the format that is appropriate for that culture.","pos":[18625,18724]},{"pos":[18998,19021],"content":"Persist dates and times","linkify":"Persist dates and times","nodes":[{"content":"Persist dates and times","pos":[0,23]}]},{"content":"You should never persist date and time data in a format that can vary by culture.","pos":[19023,19104]},{"content":"This is a common programming error that results in either corrupted data or a run-time exception.","pos":[19105,19202]},{"content":"The following example serializes two dates, January 9, 2013 and August 18, 2013, as strings by using the formatting conventions of the English (United States) culture.","pos":[19203,19370]},{"content":"When the data is retrieved and parsed by using the conventions of the English (United States) culture, it is successfully restored.","pos":[19371,19502]},{"content":"However, when it is retrieved and parsed by using the conventions of the English (United Kingdom) culture, the first date is wrongly interpreted as September 1, and the second fails to parse because the Gregorian calendar does not have an eighteenth month.","pos":[19503,19759]},{"content":"You can avoid this problem in any of three ways:","pos":[20029,20077]},{"content":"Serialize the date and time in binary format rather than as a string.","pos":[20081,20150]},{"content":"Save and parse the string representation of the date and time by using a custom format string that is the same regardless of the user's culture.","pos":[20154,20298]},{"content":"Save the string by using the formatting conventions of the invariant culture.","pos":[20302,20379]},{"content":"The following example illustrates the last approach.","pos":[20381,20433]},{"content":"It uses the formatting conventions of the invariant culture returned by the static <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Globalization.CultureInfo.InvariantCulture%2A?displayProperty=nameWithType&gt;</ph> property.","pos":[20434,20615],"source":" It uses the formatting conventions of the invariant culture returned by the static <xref:System.Globalization.CultureInfo.InvariantCulture%2A?displayProperty=nameWithType> property."},{"pos":[20889,20926],"content":"Serialization and time zone awareness","linkify":"Serialization and time zone awareness","nodes":[{"content":"Serialization and time zone awareness","pos":[0,37]}]},{"content":"A date and time value can have multiple interpretations, ranging from a general time (\"The stores open on January 2, 2013, at 9:00 A.M.\") to a specific moment in time (\"Date of birth: January 2, 2013 6:32:00 A.M.\").","pos":[20928,21143]},{"content":"When a time value represents a specific moment in time and you restore it from a serialized value, you should ensure that it represents the same moment in time regardless of the user's geographical location or time zone.","pos":[21144,21364]},{"content":"The following example illustrates this problem.","pos":[21366,21413]},{"content":"It saves a single local date and time value as a string in three <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>standard formats<ept id=\"p1\">](../../../docs/standard/base-types/standard-date-and-time-format-strings.md)</ept> (\"G\" for general date long time, \"s\" for sortable date/time, and \"o\" for round-trip date/time) as well as in binary format.","pos":[21414,21697],"source":" It saves a single local date and time value as a string in three [standard formats](../../../docs/standard/base-types/standard-date-and-time-format-strings.md) (\"G\" for general date long time, \"s\" for sortable date/time, and \"o\" for round-trip date/time) as well as in binary format."},{"content":"When the data is restored on a system in the same time zone as the system on which it was serialized, the deserialized date and time values accurately reflect the original value, as the output shows:","pos":[21971,22170]},{"content":"However, if you restore the data on a system in a different time zone, only the date and time value that was formatted with the \"o\" (round-trip) standard format string preserves time zone information and therefore represents the same instant in time.","pos":[22395,22645]},{"content":"Here's the output when the date and time data is restored on a system in the Romance Standard Time zone:","pos":[22646,22750]},{"content":"To accurately reflect a date and time value that represents a single moment of time regardless of the time zone of the system on which the data is deserialized, you can do any of the following:","pos":[22975,23168]},{"content":"Save the value as a string by using the \"o\" (round-trip) standard format string.","pos":[23172,23252]},{"content":"Then deserialize it on the target system.","pos":[23253,23294]},{"content":"Convert it to UTC and save it as a string by using the \"r\" (RFC1123) standard format string.","pos":[23298,23390]},{"content":"Then deserialize it on the target system and convert it to local time.","pos":[23391,23461]},{"content":"Convert it to UTC and save it as a string by using the \"u\" (universal sortable) standard format string.","pos":[23465,23568]},{"content":"Then deserialize it on the target system and convert it to local time.","pos":[23569,23639]},{"content":"Convert it to UTC and save it in binary format.","pos":[23643,23690]},{"content":"Then deserialize it on the target system and convert it to local time.","pos":[23691,23761]},{"content":"The following example illustrates each technique.","pos":[23763,23812]},{"content":"When the data is serialized on a system in the Pacific Standard Time zone and deserialized on a system in the Romance Standard Time zone, the example displays the following output:","pos":[24086,24266]},{"pos":[24489,24619],"content":"For more information, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Converting Times Between Time Zones<ept id=\"p1\">](../../../docs/standard/datetime/converting-between-time-zones.md)</ept>.","source":"For more information, see [Converting Times Between Time Zones](../../../docs/standard/datetime/converting-between-time-zones.md)."},{"pos":[24625,24657],"content":"Perform date and time arithmetic","linkify":"Perform date and time arithmetic","nodes":[{"content":"Perform date and time arithmetic","pos":[0,32]}]},{"content":"Both the <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.DateTime&gt;</ph> and <ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;xref:System.DateTimeOffset&gt;</ph> types support arithmetic operations.","pos":[24659,24760],"source":"Both the <xref:System.DateTime> and <xref:System.DateTimeOffset> types support arithmetic operations."},{"content":"You can calculate the difference between two date values, or you can add or subtract particular time intervals to or from a date value.","pos":[24761,24896]},{"content":"However, arithmetic operations on date and time values do not take time zones and time zone adjustment rules into account.","pos":[24897,25019]},{"content":"Because of this, date and time arithmetic on values that represent moments in time can return inaccurate results.","pos":[25020,25133]},{"content":"For example, the transition from Pacific Standard Time to Pacific Daylight Time occurs on the second Sunday of March, which is March 10 for the year 2013.","pos":[25135,25289]},{"content":"As the following example shows, if you calculate the date and time that is 48 hours after March 9, 2013 at 10:30 A.M.","pos":[25290,25407]},{"content":"on a system in the Pacific Standard Time zone, the result, March 11, 2013 at 10:30 A.M., does not take the intervening time adjustment into account.","pos":[2